# [MOPS](../wg/mops.html)

**IETF 125 - Bangkok, Thailand**

## Summary
The Media Operations (MOPS) Working Group met at IETF 125 to discuss the progress of its active draft on network overlays, evaluate a proposal for dynamic multicast tunneling, and receive industry updates from the Streaming Video Technology Alliance (SVTA) and MPEG Systems. The session also marked a leadership transition, with Kyle Rose stepping down and Jana Iyengar joining Leslie Daigle as co-chair.

## Key Discussion Points

### Working Group Status and Administration
*   **Chairs:** Leslie Daigle and Jana Iyengar (joining).
*   **Note Taker:** Magnus Westerlund.
*   Leslie Daigle thanked Kyle Rose for his service as co-chair since the group's inception.
*   The [MOPS Chair slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-mops-mops-chair-slides-00) were presented, and the agenda was approved without changes.

### [Network Overlays IETF125](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-mops-network-overlays-ietf125-00)
**Presenter:** Glenn Deen
**Draft:** [draft-ietf-mops-network-overlay-impacts](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-mops-network-overlay-impacts/)

*   Glenn Deen provided an update on version 03 of the document, which addresses the impact of Privacy Enhancing Technologies (PETs) on video streaming.
*   The editors received significant feedback from David Schinazi regarding the distinction between traditional VPNs and modern PETs (like MASQUE/Apple Private Relay).
*   **Technical Discussion:**
    *   A core challenge identified is that modern PETs are often designed to be hidden even from the applications running on the device to prevent malicious apps from disabling privacy features. This creates a conflict for video players that need to understand the network pipeline for efficient delivery.
    *   The document serves as a "problem statement." Solutions and remedial plans are intended for a separate follow-on document to keep the scope clear.
    *   The authors disagree with merging the definitions of VPNs and modern PETs because VPNs generally do not hide their presence from the application layer (e.g., via IP address discovery or routing tables), whereas modern PETs aim for total transparency/hiddenness.
*   **Participant Feedback:** Magnus Westerlund noted that MASQUE can be used in non-privacy-enhancing ways, such as signaling to middleboxes in cooperation with applications. He cautioned the authors to be precise about the use cases for MASQUE versus specific applications like Apple Private Relay.

### [Dynamic Internet Multicast Tunneling](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-mops-dynamic-internet-multicast-tunneling-00)
**Presenter:** Lenny Giuliano

*   Lenny Giuliano presented a proposal to solve the "middle mile" problem for multicast delivery over unicast-only networks.
*   **Problem:** Automatic Multicast Tunneling (AMT) lacks a discovery mechanism for gateways to know which relay to use for specific sources, especially when multiple relays exist.
*   **Proposed Solution:** Use BGP Extended Communities to specify the AMT relay address within the BGP route to the source. This allows routers to dynamically discover the appropriate relay to join a specific multicast flow.
*   **Technical Context:** This extends the "TreeDN" architecture (RFC 9706) from last-mile delivery to middle-mile router-to-router tunneling. It aims for a "zero-config" approach compared to static GRE tunnels.
*   **Next Steps:** While MOPS provides a good venue for architectural feedback, the work will be formally pursued in the MBONED working group.

### [SVTA Update to IETF MOPS at IETF125](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-mops-svta-update-to-ietf-mops-at-ietf125-00)
**Presenter:** Glenn Deen

*   SVTA recently merged with DASH-IF and the Ultra HD Forum.
*   **Active Work:**
    *   **Edge Caching:** Developing a specification for hosting generic cached environments at the extreme edge, requiring tighter integration with network topology (BGP awareness).
    *   **L4S Integration:** SVTA is seeking a standardized way to measure video statistics (application layer) in correlation with IP-layer L4S performance to prove the benefits of the technology.
    *   **AI in Standards:** SVTA is experimenting with using Large Language Models (LLMs) to speed up the drafting process for technical specifications, reducing the time from conception to publication.

### [MPEG Systems update](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-mops-mpeg-systems-update-00)
**Presenter:** Young Kwun

*   MPEG Systems is looking beyond traditional compression into the "adaptation" layer between applications and networks.
*   **New Exploration Areas:**
    *   **AI Metadata:** Distinguishing between human-captured and AI-generated content.
    *   **AI Model Delivery:** Methods to deliver AI models to clients for local content generation/enhancement.
    *   **Network-Friendly Containers:** Investigating if the ISO Base Media File Format (ISOBMFF) needs a successor more suited to streaming/network delivery rather than storage.
    *   **Green Streaming:** Increasing focus on reducing energy consumption in the delivery chain.
*   An MPEG workshop is planned for July 2025 in Geneva.

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **Draft Update:** The authors of `draft-ietf-mops-network-overlay-impacts` will incorporate feedback from David Schinazi and Magnus Westerlund into a version 04.
*   **Visual Enhancements:** Version 04 of the overlay draft will include more diagrams to illustrate the interaction between applications and PETs.

## Next Steps
*   The working group aims to progress `draft-ietf-mops-network-overlay-impacts` to Working Group Last Call (WGLC) by the Vienna meeting (IETF 126).
*   Participants are encouraged to review the overlay draft and provide feedback on the mailing list, particularly regarding the distinction between VPNs and newer PETs.